- Use headers for minor variations
- Maintain 2 versions simultaneously during migration
- Set sunset dates and communicate deprecation

N+1 problem: Query returns 1 parent, then triggers N queries for children instead of 1 JOIN. Classic ORM pitfall with massive performance impact.

**The problem:**

```java
@Entity
class Order {
    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.LAZY) // Default
    List<LineItem> items;
}

@Entity
class LineItem {
    Long orderId;
}

// N+1 example:
List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAll(); // 1 query: SELECT * FROM orders

for (Order order : orders) {
    List<LineItem> items = order.getItems(); // N queries: SELECT * FROM line_items WHERE order_id = ?
    for (LineItem item : items) {
        System.out.println(item.getProductName());
    }
}

// For 100 orders: 1 + 100 = 101 queries!
// Database gets hammered, huge latency
```

**Detection:**

```java
// Enable SQL logging
spring.jpa.show-sql=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.format_sql=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.use_sql_comments=true

// Output shows:
// Hibernate: SELECT o.* FROM orders o
// Hibernate: SELECT li.* FROM line_items li WHERE li.order_id = 1
// Hibernate: SELECT li.* FROM line_items li WHERE li.order_id = 2
// ... repeated 100 times

// Profiler also shows excessive DB round-trips
```

**Solutions:**

```java
// Solution 1: Eager loading
@Entity
class Order {
    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.EAGER) // JOINS automatically
    List<LineItem> items;
}

List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAll();
// Single query with JOIN - 1 query!

// But EAGER has problems:
// - Cartesian product (100 orders × 10 items = 1000 rows)
// - Can't use EAGER for multiple relationships

// Solution 2: Explicit JOIN FETCH (preferred)
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {

    @Query("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.items i")
    List<Order> findAllWithItems();
}

List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAllWithItems();
// Single query with JOIN - clean and performant

// Solution 3: Projection (only fetch what you need)
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {

    @Query("""SELECT new OrderDTO(o.id, o.date, COUNT(i.id))
              FROM Order o
              LEFT JOIN o.items i
              GROUP BY o.id""")
    List<OrderDTO> findOrderStats();
}

// Solution 4: Separate queries (when JOINs are complex)
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {

    @Query("SELECT o FROM Order o WHERE o.date > ?1")
    List<Order> findRecentOrders(LocalDate since);

    @Query("""SELECT i FROM LineItem i WHERE i.orderId IN ?1""")
    List<LineItem> findItemsForOrders(List<Long> orderIds);
}

// Usage: Reduce N+1 to 2 queries
List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findRecentOrders(LocalDate.now());
List<LineItem> items = orderRepository.findItemsForOrders(
    orders.stream().map(Order::getId).collect(toList())
);

// Solution 5: Batch fetching (Hibernate optimization)
// application.yml
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.default_batch_fetch_size=20

// Instead of 100 queries, Hibernate batches:
// SELECT * FROM line_items WHERE order_id IN (1,2,3,...,20)
// SELECT * FROM line_items WHERE order_id IN (21,22,23,...,40)
// ... etc
```

N+1 is a classic interview question because it reveals ORM understanding. Always profile queries in development.

Lazy loading defers fetching until accessed (better for large datasets, avoids unnecessary queries); Eager loading fetches immediately (fewer queries, cartesian product risk).

**Impact and trade-offs:**

```java
@Entity
class Customer {
    String name;

    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.LAZY) // Default
    List<Order> orders;
}

// LAZY example:
Customer customer = customerRepository.findById(1);
// Query: SELECT * FROM customers WHERE id = 1
// orders NOT fetched yet

if (customer.getOrders().size() > 0) {
    // Query: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE customer_id = 1
    // LAZY triggered when accessing orders
}

// EAGER example:
@Entity
class Customer {
    @OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.EAGER)
    List<Order> orders;
}

Customer customer = customerRepository.findById(1);
// Query: SELECT c.*, o.* FROM customers c
//        LEFT JOIN orders o ON c.id = o.customer_id
// orders fetched immediately

// Problem with EAGER: Cartesian product
// Customer with 5 orders: 5 duplicate rows returned
// Customer with 20 orders: 20 duplicate rows
// Scales poorly
```

**Real production scenarios:**

```java
// Scenario 1: REST endpoint returns customer
@GetMapping("/customers/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<CustomerDTO> getCustomer(@PathVariable Long id) {
    Customer customer = customerRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow();

    // If orders is LAZY: 2 queries total (good)
    // If orders is EAGER: unnecessary overhead when only customer data needed

    return ResponseEntity.ok(CustomerDTO.from(customer));
}

// Scenario 2: List all customers with orders
@GetMapping("/customers")
public ResponseEntity<List<CustomerDTO>> listCustomers() {
    List<Customer> customers = customerRepository.findAll();
    // LAZY: 101 queries (1 for customers, 100 for orders) - N+1!
    // EAGER: 1 query with JOIN, but 5000 rows if average 50 orders/customer

    return ResponseEntity.ok(customers.stream()
        .map(CustomerDTO::from)
        .collect(toList()));
}

