Interviews test knowledge of when DB optimizations fail. Always think about index usage.

Optimistic locking (version column, optimistic exceptions) assumes conflicts rare and checks on commit; Pessimistic locking (SELECT FOR UPDATE) locks immediately.

**Comparison:**

```java
// Optimistic Locking: Version-based conflict detection
@Entity
class Account {
    Long id;
    BigDecimal balance;

    @Version // Optimistic lock column
    Long version; // Incremented on every update
}

@Service
public class TransferService {

    @Transactional
    public void transfer(Long from, Long to, BigDecimal amount) {
        Account fromAccount = accountRepository.findById(from).orElseThrow();
        // version = 5

        Account toAccount = accountRepository.findById(to).orElseThrow();
        // version = 10

        // Simulate another thread updating fromAccount
        // (in real scenario: concurrent transaction)
        // SELECT ... FROM accounts WHERE id = from FOR UPDATE;

        fromAccount.setBalance(fromAccount.getBalance().subtract(amount));
        toAccount.setBalance(toAccount.getBalance().add(amount));

        accountRepository.save(fromAccount); // version = 6
        accountRepository.save(toAccount);   // version = 11
    }
}

// If another transaction modified fromAccount:
// UPDATE accounts SET balance = ?, version = 6 WHERE id = ? AND version = 5
// -- Fails if version != 5
// Throws OptimisticLockingException
// Application retries the entire transfer

// Pessimistic Locking: Lock immediately
@Repository
public interface AccountRepository extends JpaRepository<Account, Long> {

    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
    @Query("SELECT a FROM Account a WHERE a.id = ?1")
    Account findByIdForUpdate(Long id);
}

@Service
public class TransferService {

    @Transactional
    public void transfer(Long from, Long to, BigDecimal amount) {
        // SELECT ... FROM accounts WHERE id = ? FOR UPDATE
        // -- Lock acquired immediately
        Account fromAccount = accountRepository.findByIdForUpdate(from);
        // Other transactions WAIT here until lock released

        // SELECT ... FROM accounts WHERE id = ? FOR UPDATE
        Account toAccount = accountRepository.findByIdForUpdate(to);
        // Lock acquired on both accounts

        // Do transfer (no other thread can modify these rows)
        fromAccount.setBalance(fromAccount.getBalance().subtract(amount));
        toAccount.setBalance(toAccount.getBalance().add(amount));

        accountRepository.save(fromAccount);
        accountRepository.save(toAccount);
    }
    // Locks released on transaction commit
}
```

**When to use which:**

```java
// Use OPTIMISTIC when:
// - Conflicts are rare (reads much more than writes)
// - Can tolerate retry logic
// - High concurrency (many readers, few writers)
// - Non-blocking desired

@Entity
class BlogPost {
    @Version
    Long version;

    String title;
    String content;
    Long views;
}

// View count frequently updated, but edit conflicts rare
// Optimistic: many concurrent reads, occasional write
// If write conflicts with read: retry

// Use PESSIMISTIC when:
// - Conflicts are frequent (many concurrent updates)
// - Can't tolerate retries
// - Business logic requires serialization
// - Small subset of critical data

@Service
public class PaymentProcessor {

    @Transactional
    public void processPayment(Long accountId, BigDecimal amount) {
        // CRITICAL: Must execute atomically, no conflicts
        // SELECT ... FROM accounts WHERE id = ? FOR UPDATE
        Account account = accountRepository.findByIdForUpdate(accountId);

        if (account.getBalance() < amount) {
            throw new InsufficientFundsException();
        }

        account.debit(amount);
        accountRepository.save(account);

        // Lock held until commit - no other transaction can update
    }
}
```

**Performance implications:**

```
Optimistic:
- No locks held
- High throughput under low contention
- Retry overhead if conflicts occur
- Good for: reading, occasional updates

Pessimistic:
- Locks held for transaction duration
- Other transactions wait
- Lower throughput under high contention
- Good for: critical operations, frequent conflicts
```

Choice depends on conflict patterns and business requirements.

For very large tables: keyset pagination (cursor-based), limit+offset with indexed sort, or sharding. Avoid OFFSET for massive datasets—it's O(n).

**Methods:**

```java
// WRONG: Offset-based (SLOW)
@GetMapping("/orders")
public ResponseEntity<Page<Order>> getOrders(@RequestParam int page) {
    // Page 1 (offset 0): SELECT ... LIMIT 20
    // Page 100 (offset 1980): SELECT ... LIMIT 20 OFFSET 1980
    // Database still scans first 1980 rows, very slow!

    Pageable pageable = PageRequest.of(page, 20, Sort.by("id").descending());
    Page<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAll(pageable);
    return ResponseEntity.ok(orders);
}

// Benchmark
// Page 1: 10ms
// Page 100: 500ms
// Page 1000: 5 seconds (OFFSET scans through 20k rows!)

// CORRECT: Keyset pagination (cursor-based)
@GetMapping("/orders")
public ResponseEntity<List<OrderDTO>> getOrders(
    @RequestParam(required = false) Long lastId) {

    if (lastId == null) {
        lastId = Long.MAX_VALUE; // First page
    }

    // WHERE id < lastId ORDER BY id DESC LIMIT 21
    // Uses index on ID, scans in order
    List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findByIdLessThanOrderByIdDesc(lastId, PageRequest.of(0, 21));

    List<OrderDTO> results = orders.stream()
        .limit(20)
        .map(OrderDTO::from)
        .collect(toList());

    boolean hasMore = orders.size() > 20;
    Long nextLastId = hasMore ? orders.get(20).getId() : null;

    // Return results + cursor for next page
    Map<String, Object> response = Map.of(
        "orders", results,
        "nextCursor", nextLastId
    );

    return ResponseEntity.ok(response);
}

// Benchmark
// Page 1: 10ms (index scan)
// Page 100: 8ms (same index scan, just different startpoint)
// Page 1000: 7ms (still index scan, no offset!)

// Repository
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, Long> {

    List<Order> findByIdLessThanOrderByIdDesc(Long id, Pageable page);
}

// CORRECT: Timestamp-based pagination
@GetMapping("/orders/by-date")
public ResponseEntity<List<OrderDTO>> getOrdersByDate(
    @RequestParam(required = false) LocalDateTime lastCreatedAt) {

    if (lastCreatedAt == null) {
        lastCreatedAt = LocalDateTime.now();
    }

    // WHERE created_at < ? ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 21
    List<Order> orders = orderRepository
        .findByCreatedAtLessThanOrderByCreatedAtDesc(lastCreatedAt, PageRequest.of(0, 21));

    List<OrderDTO> results = orders.stream()
        .limit(20)
        .map(OrderDTO::from)
        .collect(toList());

    LocalDateTime nextLastCreatedAt = orders.size() > 20 ? orders.get(20).getCreatedAt() : null;

    return ResponseEntity.ok(Map.of(
        "orders", results,
        "nextCursor", nextLastCreatedAt
    ));
}

// SCALABLE: Sharded pagination
// For table with billions of rows: partition by key
